Approximately 4,207 PG&E Customers in Humboldt County may be affected by a Public Safety Power Shutoff (PSPS) that may start tonight around midnight and last until Wednesday evening. See the Humboldt County Office of Emergency Services page and https://pge.com for detailed information.

At this time only one school is predicted to be affected -- Bridgeville -- but due to the nature of distance learning, this PSPS may affect school operations in different and unpredictable ways. For information about your school, please contact the school or district office.

Responding to concerns from our Spanish-speaking community members regarding COVID-19, LatinoNet, Centro del Pueblo and the Humboldt County Department of Health & Human Services have partnered to offer a virtual town hall Monday, Aug. 31, from 6 to 7:30 p.m.

Communication is the key to education!

HCOE is looking for a multitalented and motivated individual with a passion for supporting education to lead a talented team in its Communications Center.

Under the leadership of the County Superintendent of Schools, the Communications Manager/Public Information Officer is responsible for communicating the Office of Education’s vision, mission, goals and objectives to the community, fostering relationships with the community and with media partners, and overseeing a team with diverse responsibilities and talents in the areas of Communications, Graphic Design, Multimedia, Web Design, and Printing Services.

Employees at HCOE enjoy competitive salaries and excellent retirement and health benefits. To learn more or apply, visit https://employment.hcoe.org/jobs/view/3828/. The application deadline is Friday, Aug. 7

shared_text:
California Department of Education
June 16 at 1:06 PM ·

Update: California Surgeon General Dr. Nadine Burke Harris will join "Student Support Circle: Institutional Racism and Implicit Bias" hosted by the CDE and State Superintendent Tony Thurmond, in partnership with National Equity Project.

Middle and high school age students are encouraged to join this Thursday, June 18 at 4 p.m, on Facebook Live. It will feature students from across the state speaking about what they've experienced and talk about practical solutions to institutional racism and implicit basis in public schools.

The CDE recently created an email address for our communities to have their voices heard regarding institutional racism. Please submit your ideas and feedback to createracialjustice@gmail.com.
text:
California Department of Education
June 16 at 1:06 PM ·

Update: California Surgeon General Dr. Nadine Burke Harris will join "Student Support Circle: Institutional Racism and Implicit Bias" hosted by the CDE and State Superintendent Tony Thurmond, in partnership with National Equity Project.

Middle and high school age students are encouraged to join this Thursday, June 18 at 4 p.m, on Facebook Live. It will feature students from across the state speaking about what they've experienced and talk about practical solutions to institutional racism and implicit basis in public schools.

The CDE recently created an email address for our communities to have their voices heard regarding institutional racism. Please submit your ideas and feedback to createracialjustice@gmail.com.

post_text: Check out the virtual Industrial Technology Showcase!
shared_text:
HCOE.ORG
2020 Slideshow | Gary Roberts Industrial Technology Showcase

Humboldt County Maker Movement
June 1 at 10:40 AM ·

HCOE Education at Work and Student Events would like to invite you to view the annual Gary Robert's Industrial Technology Showcase of Excellence 2020 in its first ever VIRTUAL format.

Traditionally this event takes place in late May or early June as a way to celebrate high school Industrial Technology students in woodworking, metal, architectural design/drafting, industrial prototyping, and automotive technology. Students are nominated based on passion for their trade, pride in workmanship, innovation, and work ethic.

This year teachers were encouraged to submit projects/students they wanted to showcase "virtually". A big thanks for those teachers who participated! Please take a moment to view the slideshow and celebrate the excellent work of the teachers and students in these wonderful programs.
https://hcoe.org/it-showcase/2020-slideshow/

post_text: #BeTheLightHDN HDN schools around the North Coast will turn on their stadium lights tonight at 8:20 pm to honor the senior class athletes of 2020 who had their seasons cut short due to COVID-19. The lights will stay on for 20 minutes. This is not an event to attend, but a way to recognize the student-athletes of 2020. Students, their families and the community are asked to keep the athletes and everyone impacted by COVID-19 in their thoughts. As of Thursday night, Arcata, Del Norte, Eureka, Ferndale, Fortuna, McKinleyville, South Fork, and St. Bernard’s have all agreed to participate.
text: #BeTheLightHDN HDN schools around the North Coast will turn on their stadium lights tonight at 8:20 pm to honor the senior class athletes of 2020 who had their seasons cut short due to COVID-19. The lights will stay on for 20 minutes. This is not an event to attend, but a way to recognize the student-athletes of 2020. Students, their families and the community are asked to keep the athletes and everyone impacted by COVID-19 in their thoughts. shared_text:
Blue Lake Rancheria Tribe
April 3 at 11:25 AM ·

While schools are closed and shelter-in-place remains in order, Pathmakers is actively working on improving our educational programming that serves the Humboldt region, with social distancing in mind.

Our team is exploring ways to provide content virtually, to keep kids engaged in STEAM (science, technology, arts, math) activities while indoors.

Pathmakers will keep you updated on summer programming and event planning changes as things move forward.

Please take care and know Pathmakers is sheltering in place as a social responsibility to our elders and the community as a whole.

Pathmakers offers culturally responsive makerspace programming for native and non-native youth in grades K-12 throughout Humboldt County.
The 4-year program was developed by the Blue Lake Rancheria Tribe, Humboldt County Office of Education, and the Northern Humboldt Union High School District.

Humboldt County Office of Education is in support of recent recommendations from Governor Newsom and Superintendent Thurmond to extend distant learning opportunities for the remainder of the school year. HCOE will continue to partner with local districts to improve upon distant learning programs, services, and supports for schools and families in our community. Each district will be meeting with their respective boards to announce their individual plans for their school sites.

Superintendent of Schools, Dr. Chris Hartley says it best and reassures, “School is not over. Humboldt County schools are the heartbeat of our communities. They will continue to provide essential services for students and families by embracing innovation and collaboration.”

For more information on resources, meal distribution schedules, or on-line activities visit hcoe.org/covid-19. We are updating the site daily to give you access to high quality vetted resources. To read the full press release that was issued today.

#WeAreInThisTogether
http://ow.ly/cGA050z3OzG

Latest update: Humboldt County may not lose power tonight. Please note the disclosure at the bottom of the below post though and refer to our spreadsheet for up-to-date school status information:

https://hcoe.org/psps
shared_text:
Humboldt County Office of Emergency Services
October 29, 2019 at 5:21 PM ·

Update as of Tuesday at 5:15 p.m.
According to PG&E representatives, “Due to diminished weather conditions, Humboldt County is now beneath the wind threshold for a Public Safety Power Shutoff (PSPS).” The information we are receiving from PG&E is that Humboldt County is no longer in scope and will remain with power throughout the evening. Continue to be prepared for future outages and follow updates from the Humboldt County Office of Emergency Services (OES).

There are still communities in Humboldt who have not been restored from the previous PSPS. PG&E advises they hope to re-energize tonight.

At this time the National Weather Service does not foresee any weather patterns that would result in a PSPS event in the near future.

This release is intended to update the public on PSPS activity information provided by PG&E. This office is not able to guarantee the accuracy of the information provided and the public should consider this release as general information and be prepared for a PSPS event that may have different timing and/or duration than predicted.

#HumCoPSPS

shared_text:
Humboldt County Office of Emergency Services
October 27, 2019 at 1:31 PM ·

Hey, Humboldt. Good news and (mostly) bad news.

Good news:

-We have received a weather “all clear” for this weekend’s wind event.
-PG&E will begin restoration efforts in areas of Humboldt County as conditions allow.

Bad news:

-A second wind event is forecast to begin at 6 a.m. on Tuesday, Oct. 29.
-PG&E is looking at another Public Safety Power Shutoff prior to the beginning of this weather event.

Be prepared:

Based on PG&E’s latest information, we expect a small window of time between restoration from the current outage before powering down again on Tuesday.

During the window, we suggest:
-Restocking emergency supplies including medication, food, water, fuel, etc.
-Charging all devices.
-Making arrangements for medical needs.
-Signing up for Humboldt ALERT at humboldtgov.org/alerts
-Following @HumboldtCountyOES on Facebook and Twitter for the latest information.

Keep in mind, the information and weather is ever-changing, and we are giving you information as soon as we get it.

#DontShootTheMessenger
#HumCoPSPS
#WeAreAllInThisTogether

Humboldt County DHHS
October 24, 2019 at 2:42 PM ·

Are you signed up for PG&E’s Public Safety Power Shutoff (PSPS) alerts? Now is a good time to make sure you’re signed up for the utility’s outage warning system. If you’re a direct PG&E customer, visit pge.com/mywildfirealerts or phone 866-743-6589 to sign up for PSPS alerts which are available by text, email and voice. Additionally, you can now sign up for PG&E's PSPS alerts even if you're not a direct PG&E account holder. The new system alerts participants by zip code. Visit pge.com/pspszipcodealerts or call 877-9000-PGE.

post_text: If you've gotten a letter about more outages this week, it is fake.
shared_text:
Humboldt County Office of Emergency Services
October 14, 2019 at 11:50 AM ·

We are getting a lot of questions about mailed letters that appear to be from PG&E notifying three counties that a power outage is scheduled October 16-19. This is a fake letter modeled after the real maintenance outage letters that PG&E sends in advance of a scheduled outage for a shorter duration in a smaller area. There are no scheduled outages for Humboldt County this week.

Please share!

Edit: All reports of the letter appear to include the same image shared online, and we do not have any reports from individuals who received the fake letter in the mail. This is a good reminder to make sure that information that we share or repost online is from a credible source.

Today the preschool children and staff at Glen Paul hosted a visit with the children and staff of Sweet Peas Learning Center. The children at Sweet Peas enjoyed riding the big yellow school bus to Glen Paul School. All the children enjoyed a sing-a-long, snack and outside play on Glen Paul’s expansive playground.

This is the start of an ongoing friendship between the children and staff at the two schools. Thank you to the preschool staff at both schools for planning this opportunity for the students. HCOE appreciates the support and community partnership with Sweet Peas Learning Center.

post_text: Catch Marlee Mansfield travelling around Humboldt County in the awesome Mobile Pathmakers classroom!
shared_text:
Blue Lake Rancheria Tribe
August 29, 2019 at 9:52 AM ·

“We can roll out all of our curriculum and be able to deliver it right there on the spot.”

Mobile Pathmakers is essentially a “classroom on wheels,” ⁠
bringing culturally responsive makerspace activities to schools, summer camps, and community events.⁠

Full Pathmakers Documentary Part 7: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YbGA-V4j_yM&t=31s

⁠Pathmakers is an education program that focuses on “hands-on learning,” where students are presented with design challenges and given the opportunity to create and invent their own solutions.⁠
The 4-year program was developed by the Blue Lake Rancheria, Humboldt County Office of Education, and Northern Humboldt Union High School District.

post_text: We are all rooting for you, Michael!
shared_text:
Eureka City Schools
July 26, 2019 at 2:08 PM ·

HUGE congratulations to Michael Davies-Hughes, Assistant Superintendent Educational Services at Eureka City Schools, for not only qualifying for his next RAAM (Race Across America) race (June 2020), but coming in FIRST PLACE in the qualifier, Race Across Oregon, this past weekend! The qualifier was a 1,000 km loop course with nearly 50,000 feet of climbing! In June 2018, Michael and his Team Red Dragon competed in his first RAAM and, in doing so, raised $30,000 for the Early Literacy Program. For his June 2020 RAAM, Michael will be fundraising for Hopecam, which uses technology to connect children undergoing treatment for cancer with their friends at school. It has made a difference in the lives of 2,000 cancer-fighting students nationwide. Michael will be racing each day in honor of a named child. Eureka City Schools greatly appreciates Michael’s dedication to bettering the lives of children, both at work and in his personal life. Congratulations, Michael, and happy training! Only 326 days until RAAM! (Photo Credit: Race Across Oregon)

#STEAM is an educational approach to learning that uses #Science, #Technology, #Engineering the #Arts and #Mathematics as access points for guiding student inquiry, dialogue, and critical thinking. Through STEAM, students take thoughtful risks, engage in experiential learning, persist in problem-solving, embrace collaboration, and work through the creative process.
When given the opportunity, there is no limit to what a child can create.
